Problem Statement

Business Context

Understanding customer personality and behavior is pivotal for businesses to enhance customer satisfaction and increase revenue. Segmentation based on a customer's personality, demographics, and purchasing behavior allows companies to create tailored marketing campaigns, improve customer retention, and optimize product offerings.

A leading retail company with a rapidly growing customer base seeks to gain deeper insights into their customers' profiles. The company recognizes that understanding customer personalities, lifestyles, and purchasing habits can unlock significant opportunities for personalizing marketing strategies and creating loyalty programs. These insights can help address critical business challenges, such as improving the effectiveness of marketing campaigns, identifying high-value customer groups, and fostering long-term relationships with customers.

With the competition intensifying in the retail space, moving away from generic strategies to more targeted and personalized approaches is essential for sustaining a competitive edge.

Objective

In an effort to optimize marketing efficiency and enhance customer experience, the company has embarked on a mission to identify distinct customer segments. By understanding the characteristics, preferences, and behaviors of each group, the company aims to:

  1. Develop personalized marketing campaigns to increase conversion rates.
  2. Create effective retention strategies for high-value customers.
  3. Optimize resource allocation, such as inventory management, pricing strategies, and store layouts.

As a data scientist tasked with this project, your responsibility is to analyze the given customer data, apply machine learning techniques to segment the customer base, and provide actionable insights into the characteristics of each segment.

Data Dictionary

The dataset includes historical data on customer demographics, personality traits, and purchasing behaviors. Key attributes are:

  1. Customer Information

    • ID: Unique identifier for each customer.
    • Year_Birth: Customer's year of birth.
    • Education: Education level of the customer.
    • Marital_Status: Marital status of the customer.
    • Income: Yearly household income (in dollars).
    • Kidhome: Number of children in the household.
    • Teenhome: Number of teenagers in the household.
    • Dt_Customer: Date when the customer enrolled with the company.
    • Recency: Number of days since the customers last purchase.
    • Complain: Whether the customer complained in the last 2 years (1 for yes, 0 for no).

  2. Spending Information (Last 2 Years)

    • MntWines: Amount spent on wine.
    • MntFruits: Amount spent on fruits.
    • MntMeatProducts: Amount spent on meat.
    • MntFishProducts: Amount spent on fish.
    • MntSweetProducts: Amount spent on sweets.
    • MntGoldProds: Amount spent on gold products.

  3. Purchase and Campaign Interaction

    • NumDealsPurchases: Number of purchases made using a discount.
    • AcceptedCmp1: Response to the 1st campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp2: Response to the 2nd campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp3: Response to the 3rd campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp4: Response to the 4th campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • AcceptedCmp5: Response to the 5th campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).
    • Response: Response to the last campaign (1 for yes, 0 for no).

  4. Shopping Behavior

    • NumWebPurchases: Number of purchases made through the companys website.
    • NumCatalogPurchases: Number of purchases made using catalogs.
    • NumStorePurchases: Number of purchases made directly in stores.
    • NumWebVisitsMonth: Number of visits to the companys website in the last month.

data['Days_Since_Joined'] = (today - data['Dt_Customer']).dt.days

# Sanity check

Summary:

  • After analyzing the distribution of the Income variable, we observed that it was slightly right-skewed and contained some outliers. Therefore we chose to impute the missing values using the median, which is more robust to outliers than the mean. (Alternatively, since the missing values only made up 1% of the data it could have also been dropped)
  • The ID column was dropped because ID carries no useful infromation for clustering and
  • The Z_CostContact, and Z_Revenue columns were dropped because they both contained only one unique value across rows which offered no varianace or discrminative power for clustering
  • The Dt_Customer column was converted to a new feature Days_Since_Joined which better supports clustering and time-based analysis
  • The orginal Dt_Customer column was dropped

K-means Clustering

In[89]:
selected_data = pca_data

inertia = []
k_range = range(1, 11)

# Loop through the different values of K
for k in k_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
    kmeans.fit(selected_data)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Create Elbow plot to find optimal K
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(k_range, inertia, marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (k)')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
In[90]:
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# Check which K had the highest silhoutte score
for k in [2, 3, 4, 5]:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42).fit(selected_data)
    score = silhouette_score(selected_data, kmeans.labels_)
    print(f"k={k}, silhouette score: {score:.3f}")

profile_vars = ['Income', 'Kidhome', 'NumWebVisitsMonth', 'NumStorePurchases', 'NumCatalogPurchases', 'NumWebPurchases', 'MntMeatProducts', 'MntGoldProds']

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 60))

# Loop through the selected features and create a boxplot by cluster
for i, col in enumerate(profile_vars):
    plt.subplot(len(profile_vars), 1, i + 1)
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x='Cluster', y=col, palette='Set2')
    plt.title(f'{col} by Cluster')
    plt.tight_layout()

plt.show()
In[95]:
# Scale select features
profile_vars = ['Income','Kidhome', 'NumWebVisitsMonth', 'NumStorePurchases', 'NumCatalogPurchases', 'NumWebPurchases', 'MntMeatProducts', 'MntGoldProds', 'MntFruits', 'MntWines', 'MntSweetProducts']
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled_features = scaler.fit_transform(data[profile_vars])

# Create a dataframe with scaled values + cluster labels
scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(scaled_features, columns=profile_vars)
scaled_df['Cluster'] = data['Cluster']

# Group and average
scaled_summary = scaled_df.groupby('Cluster').mean().T

# Plot
scaled_summary.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(16, 8), width=0.75)
plt.title('Cluster Profiling (Scaled Features)')
plt.ylabel('Standardized Feature Value')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.grid(axis='y')
plt.legend(title='Cluster', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
Observations:

Cluster 0:

  • High Income
  • Fewer children
  • Above average spending across meat & gold products
  • High active across all purchasing channels
  • Above average catalog purchases

These are the premium high engagment customers

Cluster 1:

  • Low income
  • More children
  • Below average spend on products
  • Lower activity in all shopping channels
  • Higher web visits below average store purchases

These are the budget-conscious lower-engagement customers and have more kids

Business Recommendations

For Cluster 0: The store should reward their high engagement and aim to retain these high value customers with something like a loyalty program and rewards/perks. They also respond well to catalogs.

For Cluster 1: We may need to conduct some more studies to further understand the data. From the current data it seems like their spending is below average. It also appears that this cluster mainly does thier shopping through the store's website. This could mean that the company may need to revamp the current website and increase the website's appeal to homes with kids to increase spending, but the data isn't sufficient to fully support that statement yet. For this cluster the store should also look into offering family discounts, and promoting value based products because this customer base seems to have a lower amount of disposable income and tighter budgets.
